05371nam a22006375i 9781399508674DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023stk    fo  d z      eng d  a97813995086747 a10.1515/97813995086742doi  a(DE-B1597)651481  a(OCoLC)1390750879  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  astkcGB-SCT 7aHIS0020002bisacsh04a229.9132231 aDugan, Elena, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Apocalypse of the Birds :b1 Enoch and the Jewish Revolt against Rome /cElena Dugan. 1aEdinburgh : bEdinburgh University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (280 p.) :b34 B/W illustrations 25 tables and 9 black and white images  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aEdinburgh Studies in Religion in Antiquity00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgements -- tIntroduction: Absence of Evidence or Evidence of Absence? -- t1 On Subsidiary Works, Absent and Present from our Documents -- t2 The Nature of the Beast: Literary Evidence for Animal Apocalypse(s) of Enoch -- t3 Material Evidence for Animal Apocalypse(s) of Enoch -- t4 Dating the Animal Apocalypses -- t5 The Early Christian Readers of the Apocalypse of the Birds -- t6 The Apocalypse of the Birds and the First Jewish Revolt -- t7 On Animal Apocalypses in the First Century and Beyond -- tAppendix: An Annotated Apocalypse of the Birds (1 Enoch 89.59–90.42) -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIdentifies and contextualises a new work within the Animal Apocalypse, dated to the dawn of the First Jewish RevoltIdentifies a new source for the study of the Jewish Revolt, establishing the high hopes of the revolutionaries before the ultimate collapse of the movementPursues a unified and cross-disciplinary study of the apocalyptic and historiographic literature of Jews and Christians (or Jesus-followers) in the first-century CEAdvances a methodology for the study of ancient fragments, such as the Dead Sea Scrolls, that privileges our extant material evidence in the construction of literary wholesReimagines the Animal Apocalypse of Enoch as a lively literary tradition with multiple identifiable sites of growth: including the Vision of the Beasts, and the Apocalypse of the BirdsExplores the potential and pitfalls of historical-apocalyptic texts in guiding methodological discussions of datingThis book identifies a new apocalyptic work—the Apocalypse of the Birds—contained in the Animal Apocalypse (1 Enoch 85-90), and argues that it is born of the chaotic Jewish-Christian world of the first-century CE. Through close analysis of texts and manuscripts in Ge’ez, Greek, Aramaic, and Hebrew, alongside historical and numismatic evidence, the book situates the Apocalypse of the Birds alongside literature and historiography of the first-century CE. It argues that the Apocalypse of the Birds belongs to the heady early days of the First Jewish Revolt, and represents crucial evidence for the early optimism of the revolutionaries, the dynamic and progressive evolution of the Animal Apocalyptic tradition, and the blurred and porous boundaries between Jew and Jesus-follower in the first-century CE.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aJewsxHistoryyRebellion, 66-73. 4aClassics & Ancient History. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh1 aDugan, Elena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Classical Studies 2023 Englishz978311131908708